Perfect! Now I have enough information to provide a comprehensive summary. Let me compile all the findings:

## Channel Plugin Structure Analysis: IRC, Telegram, and Nostr

Based on my thorough exploration of the OpenClaw bundled channel plugins, here's a comprehensive guide to the plugin architecture:

### 1. Overall Directory Structure

Each channel plugin follows this consistent structure:

```
extensions/<plugin-id>/
├── openclaw.plugin.json          # Plugin manifest
├── package.json                  # npm package metadata
├── index.ts                       # Main entry point (exports plugin)
├── api.ts                         # Public barrel export (for core/tests)
├── setup-entry.ts                # Setup plugin entry point
├── channel-config-api.ts          # Config schema exports (optional)
├── runtime-api.ts                 # Private runtime barrel (optional)
├── test-api.ts                    # Test utilities (for complex plugins)
├── test-support.ts                # Test harness helpers
├── allow-from.ts                  # Allow-from normalization exports
├── update-offset-runtime-api.ts   # Runtime-specific APIs (if needed)
└── src/
    ├── channel.ts                 # Main ChannelPlugin implementation
    ├── channel.setup.ts           # Setup flow plugin
    ├── runtime.ts                 # Runtime state management
    ├── types.ts                   # TypeScript type definitions
    ├── config-schema.ts           # Zod config schema
    ├── accounts.ts                # Account resolution logic
    ├── send.ts                    # Outbound message sending
    ├── inbound.ts                 # Inbound message handling
    ├── normalize.ts               # Target ID normalization
    ├── policy.ts                  # Access policy resolution
    ├── setup-core.ts              # Setup input processing
    ├── setup-surface.ts           # Setup wizard UI prompts
    ├── probe.ts                   # Connection testing
    ├── monitor.ts                 # Connection monitoring
    ├── bot/                       # (Telegram-specific) Bot framework
    ├── test-support/              # (Telegram-specific) Test helpers
    └── [*.test.ts]                # Extensive unit tests
```

### 2. Plugin Manifest (`openclaw.plugin.json`)

Simple, minimal configuration:

```json
{
  "id": "irc",
  "channels": ["irc"],
  "configSchema": {
    "type": "object",
    "additionalProperties": false,
    "properties": {}
  }
}
```

### 3. Package.json Configuration

The `openclaw` block in package.json defines plugin behavior:

**IRC (Minimal)**
```json
{
  "openclaw": {
    "extensions": ["./index.ts"],
    "setupEntry": "./setup-entry.ts",
    "channel": {
      "id": "irc",
      "label": "IRC",
      "selectionLabel": "IRC (Server + Nick)",
      "detailLabel": "IRC",
      "docsPath": "/channels/irc"
    }
  }
}
```

**Telegram (Full-featured)**
```json
{
  "openclaw": {
    "extensions": ["./index.ts"],
    "setupEntry": "./setup-entry.ts",
    "channel": {
      "id": "telegram",
      "label": "Telegram",
      "markdownCapable": true,
      "selectionExtras": ["https://openclaw.ai"]
    },
    "bundle": {
      "stageRuntimeDependencies": true
    }
  }
}
```

**Nostr (Published/Installable)**
```json
{
  "install": {
    "npmSpec": "@openclaw/nostr",
    "minHostVersion": ">=2026.4.1"
  },
  "release": {
    "publishToNpm": true
  }
}
```

### 4. Entry Points and Registration

**index.ts - Main Plugin Entry**
```typescript
import { defineChannelPluginEntry } from "openclaw/plugin-sdk/core";

export default defineChannelPluginEntry({
  id: "irc",
  name: "IRC",
  description: "IRC channel plugin",
  plugin: ircPlugin as ChannelPlugin,
  setRuntime: setIrcRuntime,
});

export { ircPlugin } from "./src/channel.js";
export { setIrcRuntime } from "./src/runtime.js";
```

**setup-entry.ts - Setup Plugin Entry**
```typescript
import { defineSetupPluginEntry } from "openclaw/plugin-sdk/core";

export default defineSetupPluginEntry(ircPlugin);
```

### 5. Barrel Exports

**api.ts - Public API for core/tests**
```typescript
// IRC
export * from "./src/accounts.js";
export * from "./src/setup-surface.js";

// Telegram (much larger)
export * from "./src/account-inspect.js";
export * from "./src/accounts.js";
export * from "./src/action-threading.js";
export * from "./src/allow-from.js";
export * from "./src/api-fetch.js";
// ... 20+ more exports
export type { TelegramButtonStyle, TelegramInlineButtons } from "./src/button-types.js";
```

**runtime-api.ts - Private runtime barrel**
```typescript
// Re-exports from plugin SDK with local customizations
export {
  buildBaseChannelStatusSummary,
  createAccountStatusSink,
  chunkTextForOutbound,
  // ... framework types
} from "openclaw/plugin-sdk/irc";
```

### 6. Channel Plugin Registration and Capabilities

The core plugin is built with `createChatChannelPlugin`:

**IRC Example - Minimal**
```typescript
export const ircPlugin: ChannelPlugin<ResolvedIrcAccount, IrcProbe> = 
  createChatChannelPlugin({
    base: {
      id: "irc",
      meta: { ...meta, quickstartAllowFrom: true },
      setup: ircSetupAdapter,
      setupWizard: ircSetupWizard,
      capabilities: {
        chatTypes: ["direct", "group"],
        media: true,
        blockStreaming: true,
      },
      reload: { configPrefixes: ["channels.irc"] },
      configSchema: IrcChannelConfigSchema,
      // ... messaging, resolver, directory, status, gateway
    },
    pairing: { text: { ... } },
    security: { resolveDmPolicy, collectWarnings },
    outbound: {
      base: {
        deliveryMode: "direct",
        chunker: chunkTextForOutbound,
        chunkerMode: "markdown",
        textChunkLimit: 350,  // MESSAGE SIZE LIMIT
      },
      attachedResults: { channel: "irc", sendText, sendMedia },
    },
  });
```

**Telegram Example - Advanced**
```typescript
export const telegramPlugin = createChatChannelPlugin({
  base: {
    ...createTelegramPluginBase({
      setupWizard: telegramSetupWizard,
      setup: telegramSetupAdapter,
    }),
    allowlist: buildDmGroupAccountAllowlistAdapter({...}),
    bindings: { compileConfiguredBinding, matchInboundConversation },
