### 15. Key Differences Between Plugins

| Feature | IRC | Telegram | Nostr |
|---------|-----|----------|-------|
| **Chat Types** | direct, group | direct, group, channel, thread | direct (DMs only) |
| **Default Chunk Limit** | 350 chars | 4000 chars | N/A (DMs only) |
| **Markdown Support** | Converted to plain text tables | Native markdown + inline buttons | Basic markdown |
| **Reactions** | No | Yes (emoji reactions) | No |
| **Threads** | No | Yes (forum topics) | No |
| **Media** | URLs only | Photos, audio, video, stickers | None |
| **Approvals** | No | Yes (native buttons) | No |
| **Account Model** | Multiple named accounts | Single account | Single account |
| **Credentials** | Host, nick, password | Bot token | Private key |

### 16. Runtime State Management

Each plugin maintains its runtime state separately:

```typescript
// irc/src/runtime.ts
const { setRuntime: setIrcRuntime, getRuntime: getIrcRuntime } =
  createPluginRuntimeStore<PluginRuntime>("IRC runtime not initialized");

// telegram/src/runtime.ts
type TelegramChannelRuntime = {
  probeTelegram?: typeof import("./probe.js").probeTelegram;
  collectTelegramUnmentionedGroupIds?: ...;
  auditTelegramGroupMembership?: ...;
  monitorTelegramProvider?: ...;
  sendMessageTelegram?: ...;
  // ... injected at runtime
};

export type TelegramRuntime = PluginRuntime & {
  channel: PluginRuntime["channel"] & {
    telegram?: TelegramChannelRuntime;
  };
};
```

This architecture allows third-party plugins to follow the same patterns while respecting the plugin boundary defined in `/extensions/CLAUDE.md`.

